Internet Out? Ours is working if you need a place to e-learn. Woodstock Community Unit School District 200 students and teachers. Students 5th grade and younger need to be accompanied by an adult. Bring headphones and masks! And water bottles, the library's water fountains are off.

We are getting a lot of families in - we'll accommodate as best we can, and it isn't ideal but our parking lot wifi signal is still available if e-learning in the car can work for you.

post_text: As the first day of school approaches, we're fielding many questions about the Parent Portal. In any school year, this system isn't activated publicly until approximately a week after school has begun because there are many schedule changes made during the first week of school. We understand there is more anxiety about access this year with the remote learning start. We did switch to a more streamlined system over the summer. Parents will receive a letter in the mail over the next two weeks with information on creating an account and connecting to our new Powerschool Parent Portal. Thank you for your patience.

post_text:
Our administrative team is compiling a list of FAQs based on parent questions, which we will post on our website and link here. Thank you for sharing your concerns and questions.

We are listening and have heard many valid, important questions that we will try to answer. These are hard decisions for everyone. We get it. We're parents, too. Some details will still be worked out in the coming weeks, but we will do the best we can to answer your concerns.
text:
Our administrative team is compiling a list of FAQs based on parent questions, which we will post on our website and link here. Thank you for sharing your concerns and questions.

We are listening and have heard many valid, important questions that we will try to answer. These are hard decisions for everyone. We get it. We're parents, too. Some details will still be worked out in the coming weeks, but we will do the best we can to answer your concerns.

post_text: We appreciate your patience regarding our plans for the 2020-2021 school year. The Board of Education met Monday evening to go over the plans and provide input. Our administrative team is updating plans based on that input and will be presenting the information on the overall plans directly to our families this week. Teams of administrators, teachers, social workers, psychologists, nurses and many others are still meeting to fine tune more specific details over the coming weeks, which we will also be communicating. We appreciate all of the hard work that goes into preparing for this fall and the continued support from our District families.

Racial & Diversity Forums:
a community conversation for Woodstock residents

Stage Left Café on the Woodstock Square

Tuesday, July 14, 2020, 7:00pm
Thursday, July 23, 2020, 4:00pm
Thursday, July 30, 2020, 7:00pm

Mayor Brian Sager invites all interested Woodstock residents to one of three planned in-person forums to engage in sincere, thought-provoking dialogue about the challenges and opportunities associated with ongoing racial and diversity issues across the country.

The forums will be held at Stage Left Café with distancing in place; masks are required for all attendees. Each forum is limited to 20 individuals and RSVPs are required by calling 815-338-4302.
Participants representing a range of opinions and experiences are encouraged to contribute to these conversations. Please join us to share your own thoughts and feelings as we respectfully explore all sentiments regarding these difficult topics.

Woodstock, Illinois, Woodstock Police Department, The Woodstock Independent, Woodstock Chamber of Commerce & Industry Woodstock Community Unit School District 200

post_text: Teacher Laura Bianchi's summer school class for 1-3 graders has been learning about space and particularly about women and women of color who work in the industry. Tiera Fletcher, a 25-year-old Boeing engineer, is one of the lead engineers working on NASA's Space Launch System to put an astronaut on Mars. Students read a book about Fletcher and asked her questions via Twitter. Ms. Fletcher was kind enough to answer them back!

Real Woodstock
June 11 at 1:49 PM ·

In Woodstock, Illinois, we are committed to the success of every child. From kindergarten on, our dual language program enables all children to learn English and Spanish, connecting cultures and fostering unity in our community.

“Because the kids have grown up in this program, they don’t see themselves as different from one another. It’s beyond tolerance, it’s the norm for these kids. It opens them up to being open to other cultures in the future.” Liz Instefjord, Second Grade teacher, Westwood Elementary School

City of Woodstock - City Hall
May 20 at 3:29 PM ·

NEW ROUTE FOR PARADE!

Event organizer Chris Gehrke and the VFW, will be hosting a Memorial Day Parade Monday, May 25th. This will not be the typical parade due to COVID-19 and Governor Pritzker’s Executive Orders. But, instead, this will be a cruising parade through town, around the Square, past the cemetery and through Emricson Park.

Interested participants are asked to meet in the parking lot(s) of Northwood Middle School, Verda aDierzen, Mary Endres at 10:30 AM where they will line up; the parade will be leaving the site at 11:00 AM. Vehicles may be tastefully decorated to honor the men and women who died serving our country.

Please practice safe distancing while watching the parade.

SIBLING HEROES!

There are many heroes in times of crisis. Right now, health care professionals top the list. We're proud of our District 200 alumni who've devoted their careers to caring for others.

Second Lieutenant Alan Hafer is a 2014 Woodstock High grad serving in the U.S. Army as a registered nurse at William Beaumont Army Medical Center at Fort Bliss, El Paso, Texas.

Amanda Hafer graduated from Woodstock High School in 2008 and is an emergency medicine clinical pharmacist in the emergency department at Morton Plant North Bay Hospital in New Port Richey, Florida.

Thank you Alan and Amanda! #D200healthcareheroes

There are many heroes in times of crisis. Right now, health care professionals top the list. We're proud of our District 200 alumni who've devoted their careers to caring for others.

JoyAnn (Oberman) Huizar is a 2004 graduate of Woodstock High School and a crisis therapist with McHenry County Crisis Services providing psychiatric assessments to patients in Northwestern Medicine's Emergency Departments in Woodstock, Huntley, McHenry; as well as Mercy Harvard and Advocate Good Shepherd. JoyAnn and the Crisis Team also provide outreach support for schools, police departments, and community members requesting critical incident stress debriefings. Stay safe, JoyAnn! #D200healthcareheroes

May 13 at 10:11 AM ·

We have had a slew of Woodstock Community Unit School District 200 students applying for e-resource cards - which is AWESOME. But! The email address entered is their D200 student email address which we can't send emails to and we have no way of contacting them. We'll put a note on the E-resource application form but if you know of any of these students, please have them reapply with a non-school email.

Need a WPL card number to access e-books, audiobooks, and digital magazines? D200 residents can fill out the e-resource card application if they don’t have a WPL card or it is missing/expired.
https://www.woodstockpubliclibrary.org/library/webform/e-resource-temporary-library-card

post_text: Sharing a post from School Board President Carl Gilmore.
shared_text:
Carl Gilmore
May 7 at 7:51 PM ·

As we wind down Teacher's Appreciation, Food Service Workers and Nurses weeks, I wanted to express the thanks of the D200 board to these groups. Before COVID-19, your efforts were appreciated, but COVID-19 revealed the character and resilience of these groups and all D200 staff. We are proud of everyone in the district, regardless of what you do, and know you will shine through the end of this school year.

Thank you!

post_text: Here's a nice community event if you have the time.
shared_text:
Rotary Club of Woodstock
May 5 at 8:58 AM ·

The Rotary Club of Woodstock and Hearthstone Communities are hosting a "Showing Your Love Parade" Thursday, May 7th, starting at 2pm to support and "show love" to the seniors in our community.

Participants will meet at the McHenry County Courthouse 2200 N. Seminary Ave Woodstock at 1:45pm. The parade will start on Rt 47 going south past Independence Health & Therapy, Hearthstone Communities and Crossroads Care Center of Woodstock. Continuing south on Rt 47 we will turn west on Lake Ave to go past Walden Oaks Walden Oaks Apartments, west on South St, north on Dean St and make 1 lap around Woodstock Square Historic District before dispersing.

The Parade is being supported by numerous other organizations like the Woodstock Police Department, Woodstock Fire/Rescue District, the Woodstock Chamber of Commerce & Industry, the City of Woodstock - City Hall, Blackhawk Area Council, Boy Scouts of America, Woodstock Independent Riders, McHenry County Sheriff's Office and Schwartz Performance Inc..

post_text: Wonderful to see so many thinking of others as we deal with the COVID-19 pandemic as a community. Carol Alfus, a retired teacher from Community High School District 155 who had two children graduate from D 200, asked Superintendent Mike Moan if she could donate face coverings to the district. Carol and about 30 others have been making face coverings, adult and pediatric sizes and donated 450 masks to be given to families. Lisa Tate, director of Nursing and Health Services, and and her staff are adding tags about the donations and CDC instructions for use. D 200 nurses will be distributing the face coverings at the food service sites at Olson and Verda Dierzen Early Learning Center.

post_text: Wonderful volunteer opportunity.
shared_text:
The Community Foundation for McHenry County
April 27 at 4:19 PM ·

During this time of the COVID-19 pandemic, it is more vital than ever that we protect our most vulnerable population. Seniors are at greater risk of complications due to COVID-19 than any other age group.

Volunteers are needed to help deliver meals to the seniors of McHenry County. Home delivered meals provide nutrition, well-being checks, and the ability for seniors to shelter at home.

For more information about volunteer opportunities in McHenry County, please contact Catholic Charities at: (815)-385-8260.

post_text: Have you been counted?
shared_text:
City of Woodstock - City Hall
April 23 at 9:05 AM ·

UPDATE - Keep Sharing!! We are on schedule to meet our 7% in 7 days!

School lunches. Plans for highways. Support for firefighters and families in need. Census results affect your community every day.

The City of Woodstock has 63% of the population who have responded to the US Census meaning 37% have yet to responded.

We have 7 days left in the month of April. Please help spread the word. 7% in 7 days would get us to 70% response by May 1st.

https://2020census.gov/

Woodstock, Illinois Real Woodstock Woodstock Square Historic District Woodstock Chamber of Commerce & Industry Woodstock Fire/Rescue District Woodstock Community Unit School District 200 The Woodstock Independent

post_text: From Mr. Jozwiak, WHS Choir Director “I'm excited to share the first ever Virtual Choir from Woodstock High School, performed by the Madrigal Singers. This is "I Don' Feel No Ways Tired", a spiritual arranged by Stacey V. Gibbs. We are happy to share its hopeful, joyful message of better days to come. I'm so proud of my students for their work to put this project together. The technological challenge of assembling these voices is daunting, and you may notice some glitches along the way. The perfectionist in me is having to let some things go, but hearing my students voices together again was awesome. I learned SO MUCH from assembling this and am excited for how I can continue to grow in using this visual/audio format to present the most refined and creative presentation possible.”
shared_text:
YOUTUBE.COM
I Don' Feel No Ways Tired
text:
From Mr. Jozwiak, WHS Choir Director “I'm excited to share the first ever Virtual Choir from Woodstock High School, performed by the Madrigal Singers. This is "I Don' Feel No Ways Tired", a spiritual arranged by Stacey V. Gibbs. We are happy to share its hopeful, joyful message of better days to come. I'm so proud of my students for their work to put this project together. The technological challenge of assembling these voices is daunting, and you may notice some glitches along the way. The perfectionist in me is having to let some things go, but hearing my students voices together again was awesome. I learned SO MUCH from assembling this and am excited for how I can continue to grow in using this visual/audio format to present the most refined and creative presentation possible.”

YOUTUBE.COM
I Don' Feel No Ways Tired

Kevin Lyons, D-200’s director of communications, explained that the district had always used technology in the classroom, including Google, ClassDojo, FlipGrid, and YouTube, but that it had never been more important than now.

“While the tools are necessary,” Lyons said, “they are only tools. Teachers are what matter most in education, and through these tools they can continue to impart their knowledge as best they can.”

The 2020 Census aims to count every individual in the United States, and that includes children. The data collected impacts many aspects of your community, including programs and services that are critical for schools, students, and younger children, such as:

Special education, Head Start, after-school programs and classroom technology. Food assistance, including free and reduced-price school lunches. Maternal and child health programs.

Please complete your 2020 Census and help make sure our school district continues to receive adequate federal funding that will help our students grow and thrive.

www.my2020census.gov

IMPORTANT MESSAGE FOR OUR FAMILIES

Breakfast and lunch will be offered to families while schools are closed during our eLearning days, March 16-20. Families may drive through or walk up to Olson Elementary School and Verda Dierzen Elementary school daily, Monday-Friday from 9-12. Families will receive both breakfast and lunch at this time.

post_text: The Board of Education Tuesday honored some outstanding winter athletes including Quinn Cynor who has earned four State Swimming medals in three years including two this season; Quinn and 200-Yard Medley Relay Team members Gunner Dunnett from WHS, Nick Phillips and Aidan Teuber from WNHS; WNHS Wrestler Isaiah Vela who went 42-6 this season earning a trip to State; WHS Basketball Player Emma Brand who joined the 1,000-point club and was a KRC All-Conference selection; and Lacey Schaffter who qualified for State in the IHSA Queen of the Hill 3-point shooting contest. Congratulations to these fine athletes!

Woodstock Police Department is eating dinner at Joe's Place.
March 8 at 11:09 AM · Marengo, IL ·

Congratulations to WPD’s 2019 Officer of the Year, Woodstock High School Resource Officer Matthew Prentice.

On Friday evening, March 6, 2020, (Left to right) Detective Sharp, Officer Prentice, Chief Lieb and Deputy Chief Parsons attended the McHenry County Chiefs of Police Association annual Holiday Dinner (make up date) where the McHenry County Officer of the Year was selected.

An additional congratulations to all of the nominees and especially the winner(s) from the Crystal Lake Police Department for their outstanding work on the tragic “AJ” investigation.

post_text:
Proud of all of these officers.
Especially Officer Michael Butler, a 2013 WHS grad!
shared_text:
Woodstock Police Department
February 27 at 9:01 PM ·

It was an evening of wins and recognition for the WPD.

On 1/9/2020 Officers’ Gallman and Butler responded to a residence in order to assist the Woodstock Fire/Rescue District for a call of a subject unresponsive and not breathing. The officers arrived on the scene first and performed life-saving CPR and utilized an automated external defibrillator to resuscitate the patient.

Tonight those officers were recognized by the Woodstock Fire Rescue District, Fire Chief Hill and the WFRD Board of Trustees for their life-saving efforts.

Congratulations to Officer Michael Butler and Officer Chris Gallman.

Well done gentlemen.

It should be noted, Trustee Spitzer (on the right) is a retired WPD Officer who served the citizens of Woodstock for decades and now continues to serve as a WFRD Trustee!

post_text:
You might see some familiar faces when visiting Chicago.
Our District is one of the key things city marketers are emphasizing in their campaign to promote Woodstock.
shared_text:
Real Woodstock
February 26 at 1:00 PM ·

Real Woodstock is about bringing people together in one of the prettiest towns anywhere. The new "Welcome Home" campaign raises awareness of Woodstock as a great place to call home. In addition to a digital campaign, Real Woodstock can be seen in Chicago on JCDecaux bus shelters, at Woodfield Mall and at Chicago Wolves games at the Allstate Arena.

The campaign highlights Woodstock's excellent schools, its charm and history and its independent, creative streak through the stories of Lori Miarecki of The Cherry Tree Inn Bed and Breakfast, community leader Pam Moorhouse, Arlene Lynes of Read Between The Lynes, the D200 Dual Language program and many more.

To learn more about Real Woodstock and living here, visit https://www.realwoodstock.com/livehere

Woodstock Chamber of Commerce & Industry Woodstock, Illinois City of Woodstock - City Hall

post_text: District 200 officials will be monitoring the weather and communicating with transportation officials this week. Students' safety is always our top priority, but decisions won't be made until the outlook is more certain. This is the first school year that District 200 has a two-hour delayed start option if weather dictates as opposed to canceling an entire day. As always, we'll notify parents by text, phone, email and our website of any closings or emergency delayed starts.
